here is a json schema for a beta cruiser:

```json
{
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
  "title": "beta cruiser",
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "name": {"type": "string"},
    "class": {"type": "string"},
    "size": {"type": "integer"},
    "speed": {"type": "number"},
    "armament": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "type": {"type": "string"},
          "caliber": {"type": "integer"},
          "quantity": {"type": "integer"}
        },
        "required": ["type", "caliber", "quantity"]
      }
    },
    "shield": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "type": {"type": "string"},
        "thickness": {"type": "number"},
        "[energy_absorption]": {"type": "number"}
      },
      "required": ["type", "thickness"]
    }
  },
  "required": ["name", "class", "size", "speed", "armament", "shield"]
}
```

in this schema, the placeholder is represented by `[energy_absorption]` in the `shield` object. this indicates that the `energy_absorption` property is optional and can be replaced with a more specific name if needed.
